# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: WarriorPath | Scene: WarriorQueen6Calshure
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "Sarah drafted her orders and handed them down."
    new "Sarah drafted her orders and handed them down."

    old "From her hands, to her commanders, to the officers and soon down to every last man and woman in her army."
    new "From her hands, to her commanders, to the officers and soon down to every last man and woman in her army."

    old "The warcamp swelled with excitement. The eagerness of soldiers too long denied a battle."
    new "The warcamp swelled with excitement. The eagerness of soldiers too long denied a battle."

    old "Perhaps only the old knew of the carnage to come, but few soldiers lived to be old."
    new "Perhaps only the old knew of the carnage to come, but few soldiers lived to be old."

    old "By early next morning, the army had completed its preparations and begun to march."
    new "By early next morning, the army had completed its preparations and begun to march."

    old "Riding near the lead, Sarah surveyed her army, trying to coax out any weakness she had perhaps missed."
    new "Riding near the lead, Sarah surveyed her army, trying to coax out any weakness she had perhaps missed."

    old "The snow slowed them down, but not by as much as she had feared."
    new "The snow slowed them down, but not by as much as she had feared."

    old "Many of the soldiers in her army were Rosannan natives, familiar with the hard winters."
    new "Many of the soldiers in her army were Rosannan natives, familiar with the hard winters."

    old "As they marched, they soon found themselves coming upon the crossroad."
    new "As they marched, they soon found themselves coming upon the crossroad."

    old "One part, poorly maintained, branched off into the Hinterlands. The main road, however, continued on to the city of Calshure."
    new "One part, poorly maintained, branched off into the Hinterlands. The main road, however, continued on to the city of Calshure."

    old "Seeing the quality of the road, Sarah was happy with the decision she had made."
    new "Seeing the quality of the road, Sarah was happy with the decision she had made."

    old "Sarah rode near the center of her army, quickly able to react to any problems encountered by the vanguard or the rear of the column."
    new "Sarah rode near the center of her army, quickly able to react to any problems encountered by the vanguard or the rear of the column."

    old "But the main road was well maintained, and so even with the heavy snowfall of the last few days, her army found little obstacle."
    new "But the main road was well maintained, and so even with the heavy snowfall of the last few days, her army found little obstacle."

    old "The wagons, heavy with cargo and equipment, rolled along on the solid stone."
    new "The wagons, heavy with cargo and equipment, rolled along on the solid stone."

    old "All around her, Sarah found her men in good spirits, laughing among themselves, at times even breaking out into song."
    new "All around her, Sarah found her men in good spirits, laughing among themselves, at times even breaking out into song."

    old "This too was part of their youth. Their inexperience."
    new "This too was part of their youth. Their inexperience."

    old "They did not know war, and so they did not fear it the way they should."
    new "They did not know war, and so they did not fear it the way they should."

    old "As her army marched along, making solid progress on the first day, Sarah could not help but shake this thought."
    new "As her army marched along, making solid progress on the first day, Sarah could not help but shake this thought."

    old "Her army, for the most part, was made up out of Rosannan natives."
    new "Her army, for the most part, was made up out of Rosannan natives."

    old "Then there were the Legions that Gilead had offered."
    new "Then there were the Legions that Gilead had offered."

    old "They marched in stoic unison. Perfectly trained. Perfectly armed."
    new "They marched in stoic unison. Perfectly trained. Perfectly armed."

    old "Almost the ideal image of what an army should be."
    new "Almost the ideal image of what an army should be."

    old "And there were her mercenaries. What they perhaps lacked in discipline they made up in experience."
    new "And there were her mercenaries. What they perhaps lacked in discipline they made up in experience."

    old "Each was seasoned by several campaigns, and each knew what war actually meant."
    new "Each was seasoned by several campaigns, and each knew what war actually meant."

    old "Out of all of them, it was her own people that she feared for."
    new "Out of all of them, it was her own people that she feared for."

    old "The Rosannan people were mostly farmers, dreaming of living easy lives with good harvests."
    new "The Rosannan people were mostly farmers, dreaming of living easy lives with good harvests."

    old "They were not born into war."
    new "They were not born into war."

    old "Not the way a Tribesman was."
    new "Not the way a Tribesman was."

    old "Tribesmen were raised from childhood to fight."
    new "Tribesmen were raised from childhood to fight."

    old "By the time they were adults, most had already served in at least two campaigns."
    new "By the time they were adults, most had already served in at least two campaigns."

    old "Not only were they experienced, their culture was also different."
    new "Not only were they experienced, their culture was also different."

    old "Rosannans feared death, but the Tribesmen almost yearned for it."
    new "Rosannans feared death, but the Tribesmen almost yearned for it."

    old "The greatest pride for a Tribesmen was a good death, and so they plunged themselves into battle with no fear."
    new "The greatest pride for a Tribesmen was a good death, and so they plunged themselves into battle with no fear."

    old "For the greatest danger to themselves was victory or earning eternal glory."
    new "For the greatest danger to themselves was victory or earning eternal glory."

    old "Her only advantage was that going off most reports was that the Tribesmen army was significantly smaller than her army."
    new "Her only advantage was that going off most reports was that the Tribesmen army was significantly smaller than her army."

    old "But Sarah also knew wars were decided by more than just numbers."
    new "But Sarah also knew wars were decided by more than just numbers."

    old "In her stomach, she felt the dread grow as they marched on the city of Calshure."
    new "In her stomach, she felt the dread grow as they marched on the city of Calshure."

    old "Marching along the main road, they progressed much faster than Sarah had even dared to hope."
    new "Marching along the main road, they progressed much faster than Sarah had even dared to hope."

    old "In under two days, they reached the city of Calshure."
    new "In under two days, they reached the city of Calshure."

    old "She spotted it the moment it crossed over the horizon, a plume of smoke rising up from it."
    new "She spotted it the moment it crossed over the horizon, a plume of smoke rising up from it."

    old "The harsh grey of the city walls stood in sharp contrast to the snow."
    new "The harsh grey of the city walls stood in sharp contrast to the snow."

    old "Her army swiftly closed the distance."
    new "Her army swiftly closed the distance."

    old "One of the scouts that had been send ahead to investigate the city, rode to meet her."
    new "One of the scouts that had been send ahead to investigate the city, rode to meet her."

    old "Sarah turned to face the scout."
    new "Sarah turned to face the scout."

    old "Report?"
    new "Report?"

    old "The city is in the hands of the Tribesmen."
    new "The city is in the hands of the Tribesmen."

    old "A regiment of Tribesmen soldiers is in control of they city, and they're out in force."
    new "A regiment of Tribesmen soldiers is in control of they city, and they're out in force."

    old "A regiment wasn't too bad in terms of numbers. Still, they had the advantage of holding the city walls."
    new "A regiment wasn't too bad in terms of numbers. Still, they had the advantage of holding the city walls."

    old "They've shut the gates to the city and they've drafted the city militia to help secure the fortifications."
    new "They've shut the gates to the city and they've drafted the city militia to help secure the fortifications."

    old "The town militia likely had little love for the Tribesmen, but they were inside, trapped with them."
    new "The town militia likely had little love for the Tribesmen, but they were inside, trapped with them."

    old "They had spend the last few years learning to listen obediently, or suffer the consequences."
    new "They had spend the last few years learning to listen obediently, or suffer the consequences."

    old "Hell, some of the younger soldiers in the militia might have lived most of their young adult lives knowing nothing but Tribe rule."
    new "Hell, some of the younger soldiers in the militia might have lived most of their young adult lives knowing nothing but Tribe rule."

    old "Sarah knew they would be loyal to her, but only if she took the city."
    new "Sarah knew they would be loyal to her, but only if she took the city."

    old "Before, they would defend it. Causing her to lose precious soldiers fighting her own people."
    new "Before, they would defend it. Causing her to lose precious soldiers fighting her own people."

    old "Anything else?"
    new "Anything else?"

    old "The scout nodded."
    new "The scout nodded."

    old "Yes, commander...I..."
    new "Yes, commander...I..."

    old "Just say it."
    new "Just say it."

    old "I...approached the city gates as close as I dared."
    new "I...approached the city gates as close as I dared."

    old "When I finally turned to leave, I heard a voice call out to me."
    new "When I finally turned to leave, I heard a voice call out to me."

    old "A voice?"
    new "A voice?"

    old "It was a Tribesman soldier. He identified himself as the leader of the regiment."
    new "It was a Tribesman soldier. He identified himself as the leader of the regiment."

    old "He...requested a meeting with you."
    new "He...requested a meeting with you."

    old "A meeting?"
    new "A meeting?"

    old "Did he say what about?"
    new "Did he say what about?"

    old "The scout shook his head."
    new "The scout shook his head."

    old "No, only that he would ride out by sunset to meet you on the open field outside of Calshure."
    new "No, only that he would ride out by sunset to meet you on the open field outside of Calshure."

    old "And that if you wanted to meet, to be there."
    new "And that if you wanted to meet, to be there."

    old "Thank you, that's all. Good work."
    new "Thank you, that's all. Good work."

    old "The scout saluted her and rode off again."
    new "The scout saluted her and rode off again."

    old "Finally, her army settled outside of Calshure, as close as they could manage without falling into the range of archers."
    new "Finally, her army settled outside of Calshure, as close as they could manage without falling into the range of archers."

    old "The city was so close, Sarah imagined she could ride out to it in only a few minutes."
    new "The city was so close, Sarah imagined she could ride out to it in only a few minutes."

    old "So close, yet with its walls up and gates shut, it might as well be a different world."
    new "So close, yet with its walls up and gates shut, it might as well be a different world."

    old "She had no doubt she could siege Calshure. Take the city by force."
    new "She had no doubt she could siege Calshure. Take the city by force."

    old "But perhaps there was value in meeting the Tribesman. Perhaps there was a different way to resolve this."
    new "But perhaps there was value in meeting the Tribesman. Perhaps there was a different way to resolve this."

    old "Then again, what if it was just distraction? Intended to delay her advance. Delay a siege by a few more days."
    new "Then again, what if it was just distraction? Intended to delay her advance. Delay a siege by a few more days."

    old "Their only real hope was to wait for reinforcements from the main Tribal army, stationed in the Capital. More than a few days away still."
    new "Their only real hope was to wait for reinforcements from the main Tribal army, stationed in the Capital. More than a few days away still."

    old "Sarah considered her options."
    new "Sarah considered her options."

    old "Meet with the Tribesman"
    new "Meet with the Tribesman"

    old "Sarah made up her mind."
    new "Sarah made up her mind."

    old "She would meet with the Tribesmen. There was nothing to lose from taking the meeting."
    new "She would meet with the Tribesmen. There was nothing to lose from taking the meeting."

    old "When the sun began to set and the light turned an orange gold, Sarah rode out ahead of her army."
    new "When the sun began to set and the light turned an orange gold, Sarah rode out ahead of her army."

    old "Plenty of people had warned her, tried to argue against her decision, warned of the dangers, but she knew she had to go alone."
    new "Plenty of people had warned her, tried to argue against her decision, warned of the dangers, but she knew she had to go alone."

    old "She couldn't send someone else, and to show up with an army of bodyguards would show a different kind of weakness. A cowardice."
    new "She couldn't send someone else, and to show up with an army of bodyguards would show a different kind of weakness. A cowardice."

    old "No, she had decided to meet him, and so she would go out alone."
    new "No, she had decided to meet him, and so she would go out alone."

    old "Sarah sat firmly in the saddle, holding the reins as she guided her horse along the road."
    new "Sarah sat firmly in the saddle, holding the reins as she guided her horse along the road."

    old "Calshure was so close, she could make out the soldiers marching along the ramparts."
    new "Calshure was so close, she could make out the soldiers marching along the ramparts."

    old "She had slung a shield along the side of her horse in case anyone would try to fire an arrow at her, though she doubted anyone would be that dishonorable."
    new "She had slung a shield along the side of her horse in case anyone would try to fire an arrow at her, though she doubted anyone would be that dishonorable."

    old "Bringing her horse to a stop, Sarah waited."
    new "Bringing her horse to a stop, Sarah waited."

    old "Finally, just as she started to worry, she saw the gates of the city open and a lone rider emerged."
    new "Finally, just as she started to worry, she saw the gates of the city open and a lone rider emerged."

    old "In just a glance, it was obvious he was a Tribesman. From the way he sat in the saddle to his clothes."
    new "In just a glance, it was obvious he was a Tribesman. From the way he sat in the saddle to his clothes."

    old "Instantly, Sarah knew that the Tribesmen had never really tried to integrate themselves."
    new "Instantly, Sarah knew that the Tribesmen had never really tried to integrate themselves."

    old "They were conquerors. They had no desire to become a part of the lands they ruled over."
    new "They were conquerors. They had no desire to become a part of the lands they ruled over."

    old "Riding swiftly, he crossed the distance in what seemed like no time at all."
    new "Riding swiftly, he crossed the distance in what seemed like no time at all."

    old "As he neared closer to her, she was surprised at his age. Older than she had expected."
    new "As he neared closer to her, she was surprised at his age. Older than she had expected."

    old "Brave of you to come here alone."
    new "Brave of you to come here alone."

    old "Brave? You're just one man."
    new "Brave? You're just one man."

    old "I'm glad to see the stories they tell of you are true."
    new "I'm glad to see the stories they tell of you are true."

    old "What stories what those be?"
    new "What stories what those be?"

    old "Those speaking of your beauty, of course."
    new "Those speaking of your beauty, of course."

    old "Perhaps you've not yet heard the stories of killing demons and mages yet."
    new "Perhaps you've not yet heard the stories of killing demons and mages yet."

    old "Yes, I have heard those too."
    new "Yes, I have heard those too."

    old "The woman that ended the old city of Bagrad."
    new "The woman that ended the old city of Bagrad."

    old "A glory many of us Tribesman would have wished to seize. You must have made a pretty fortune off what you took there."
    new "A glory many of us Tribesman would have wished to seize. You must have made a pretty fortune off what you took there."

    old "I am not in want of wealth."
    new "I am not in want of wealth."

    old "Nor am I in want of suitors, so you can keep your flattery to yourself."
    new "Nor am I in want of suitors, so you can keep your flattery to yourself."

    old "Truly, you seem in want of so little."
    new "Truly, you seem in want of so little."

    old "Tell me then, what brings a woman to these lands when she has all she can wish for."
    new "Tell me then, what brings a woman to these lands when she has all she can wish for."

    old "Sarah eyed the Tribesman. Confident, but there something about him, a hint of nervousness?"
    new "Sarah eyed the Tribesman. Confident, but there something about him, a hint of nervousness?"

    old "I have merely returned home to take back what was already mine. This is not want or greed."
    new "I have merely returned home to take back what was already mine. This is not want or greed."

    old "The Tribesman frowned."
    new "The Tribesman frowned."

    old "Yours?"
    new "Yours?"

    old "I seem to find you and your army outside in the cold, while my men sit warmly inside the gates. To whom does this city belong, really?"
    new "I seem to find you and your army outside in the cold, while my men sit warmly inside the gates. To whom does this city belong, really?"

    old "It belongs to me."
    new "It belongs to me."

    old "And should you try to put up a fight, you will die being reminded of that simple truth."
    new "And should you try to put up a fight, you will die being reminded of that simple truth."

    old "The Tribesman sat firmly in his own saddle, eyeing her."
    new "The Tribesman sat firmly in his own saddle, eyeing her."

    old "You are the first woman to ever threaten me."
    new "You are the first woman to ever threaten me."

    old "Be wise and leave the city with your men, so I won't be the last."
    new "Be wise and leave the city with your men, so I won't be the last."

    old "I cannot."
    new "I cannot."

    old "The Tribesman sighed."
    new "The Tribesman sighed."

    old "I am far from the city. Beyond the ability of my men to hear me speak, so I shall speak plainly."
    new "I am far from the city. Beyond the ability of my men to hear me speak, so I shall speak plainly."

    old "My men are eager for the fight."
    new "My men are eager for the fight."

    old "They are disciplined, strong, experienced."
    new "They are disciplined, strong, experienced."

    old "With the advantage of the city walls, I expect we can extract a heavy toll on your troops."
    new "With the advantage of the city walls, I expect we can extract a heavy toll on your troops."

    old "Perhaps not enough to keep the city, but enough to hurt your army. To weaken it for the real fight that awaits you at the capital. With Governor Kamal."
    new "Perhaps not enough to keep the city, but enough to hurt your army. To weaken it for the real fight that awaits you at the capital. With Governor Kamal."

    old "Sarah listened intently. There was some truth to what he was saying. Even a victory here could be a painful one."
    new "Sarah listened intently. There was some truth to what he was saying. Even a victory here could be a painful one."

    old "But my men...they are young."
    new "But my men...they are young."

    old "They have grown up on victory and conquest and known nothing of defeat."
    new "They have grown up on victory and conquest and known nothing of defeat."

    old "And you? What are you then?"
    new "And you? What are you then?"

    old "An old soldier. Too wise to throw away my life on a lost cause."
    new "An old soldier. Too wise to throw away my life on a lost cause."

    old "Good. You see wisdom then. Yield. Open the gates and leave with your men, I shall let them live. You have my word."
    new "Good. You see wisdom then. Yield. Open the gates and leave with your men, I shall let them live. You have my word."

    old "It cannot be so simple."
    new "It cannot be so simple."

    old "As I told you. My men are young and eager. They want to fight, even if I warn them that it will cost them their lives."
    new "As I told you. My men are young and eager. They want to fight, even if I warn them that it will cost them their lives."

    old "If anything, the thought of a great final battle excites them more than anything."
    new "If anything, the thought of a great final battle excites them more than anything."

    old "That is it then? Bloodshed, all for your people's pride?"
    new "That is it then? Bloodshed, all for your people's pride?"

    old "The Tribesman shook his head."
    new "The Tribesman shook his head."

    old "What I say now is almost treason among my people."
    new "What I say now is almost treason among my people."

    old "I want to withdraw...but if I do so, my own men will consider it weakness."
    new "I want to withdraw...but if I do so, my own men will consider it weakness."

    old "If they don't rebel in the city, they will challenge me to a duel when we ride back for the desert."
    new "If they don't rebel in the city, they will challenge me to a duel when we ride back for the desert."

    old "If I withdraw...I must be shown to do so in strength."
    new "If I withdraw...I must be shown to do so in strength."

    old "You want to retreat...yet have it be seen as an act of strength?"
    new "You want to retreat...yet have it be seen as an act of strength?"

    old "The Tribesman nodded."
    new "The Tribesman nodded."

    old "I cannot be allowed to be seen as weak. If I am...I might as well risk the fight here and now."
    new "I cannot be allowed to be seen as weak. If I am...I might as well risk the fight here and now."

    old "Wealth then. I will pay you and your men a price for a peaceful withdrawal. You can take your spoils and ride back to the desert."
    new "Wealth then. I will pay you and your men a price for a peaceful withdrawal. You can take your spoils and ride back to the desert."

    old "A payment will go a long way in easing their concerns...but I must insist on another."
    new "A payment will go a long way in easing their concerns...but I must insist on another."

    old "What do you propose then?"
    new "What do you propose then?"

    old "My people know of a ritual. Ahk'Tahar."
    new "My people know of a ritual. Ahk'Tahar."

    old "I don't know your culture. Speak to me plainly."
    new "I don't know your culture. Speak to me plainly."

    old "You will ride into the city...alone. You will meet with us under my sworn protection."
    new "You will ride into the city...alone. You will meet with us under my sworn protection."

    old "You will dine with me as a guest of honour and we shall perform the rituals."
    new "You will dine with me as a guest of honour and we shall perform the rituals."

    old "What rituals?"
    new "What rituals?"

    old "Shared food. Shared drink. And the exchange of vows."
    new "Shared food. Shared drink. And the exchange of vows."

    old "This is a ritual known for settling wars, among our people."
    new "This is a ritual known for settling wars, among our people."

    old "If we perform this...in the eyes of my people, you will not be an enemy anymore."
    new "If we perform this...in the eyes of my people, you will not be an enemy anymore."

    old "And if you are not an enemy, then leaving the city is not a retreat...it is merely us returning home."
    new "And if you are not an enemy, then leaving the city is not a retreat...it is merely us returning home."

    old "Sarah wanted to laugh at the absurdity."
    new "Sarah wanted to laugh at the absurdity."

    old "You suggest that I enter the city, by myself, with no guards?"
    new "You suggest that I enter the city, by myself, with no guards?"

    old "And all I will have is your word?"
    new "And all I will have is your word?"

    old "But you ask me to withdraw, leave the city, and trust that you don't attack me as I leave. All on your word as well."
    new "But you ask me to withdraw, leave the city, and trust that you don't attack me as I leave. All on your word as well."

    old "My word is binding. If I vow to keep you safe, none will dare to harm you."
    new "My word is binding. If I vow to keep you safe, none will dare to harm you."

    old "It's insane."
    new "It's insane."

    old "Insane?"
    new "Insane?"

    old "Think of what we will each spare the other."
    new "Think of what we will each spare the other."

    old "Your precious city of Calshure. How many do you think will die in the siege? Not just your soldiers, but townsfolk?"
    new "Your precious city of Calshure. How many do you think will die in the siege? Not just your soldiers, but townsfolk?"

    old "What do you care for my people?"
    new "What do you care for my people?"

    old "I don't, but I care for my own. Give me the excuse I need, and I can save their lives and the lives of your people."
    new "I don't, but I care for my own. Give me the excuse I need, and I can save their lives and the lives of your people."

    old "All I ask is for your trust. Meet. Speak the words. Nobody needs to die."
    new "All I ask is for your trust. Meet. Speak the words. Nobody needs to die."

    old "The proposal was insane...and yet, Sarah began to consider it."
    new "The proposal was insane...and yet, Sarah began to consider it."

    old "He seemed genuine."
    new "He seemed genuine."

    old "And if he was, this offered a chance to prevent thousands from dying."
    new "And if he was, this offered a chance to prevent thousands from dying."

    old "But if he lied, she would be beyond the walls. Nobody would be able to come save her."
    new "But if he lied, she would be beyond the walls. Nobody would be able to come save her."

    old "Sarah looked at the man as she considered her answer."
    new "Sarah looked at the man as she considered her answer."

    old "Enter Calshure with him"
    new "Enter Calshure with him"

    old "I can't believe I'm actually agreeing to this...but yes."
    new "I can't believe I'm actually agreeing to this...but yes."

    old "If you give me your word, I will enter the city with you and settle this peacefully."
    new "If you give me your word, I will enter the city with you and settle this peacefully."

    old "You are even braver than the stories."
    new "You are even braver than the stories."

    old "Sarah rode back to camp and gave word of her decision."
    new "Sarah rode back to camp and gave word of her decision."

    old "Her commanders, officers, just about everyone warned that she was making a mistake."
    new "Her commanders, officers, just about everyone warned that she was making a mistake."

    old "But Sarah was firm in her decision, and in the end, she held the final say."
    new "But Sarah was firm in her decision, and in the end, she held the final say."

    old "Riding back out from camp, Sarah met the Tribesman again outside the gate of Calshure."
    new "Riding back out from camp, Sarah met the Tribesman again outside the gate of Calshure."

    old "Well...lead the way."
    new "Well...lead the way."

    old "Pulling on the reins, he turned his horse and began to ride back to the city."
    new "Pulling on the reins, he turned his horse and began to ride back to the city."

    old "As he rode, Sarah rode besides him."
    new "As he rode, Sarah rode besides him."

    old "A silence lingered between them as they came upon the gate of the city."
    new "A silence lingered between them as they came upon the gate of the city."

    old "Each moment, Sarah imagined she would pay for her foolish decision to trust him. That some Tribesman would shoot an arrow or cut her throat."
    new "Each moment, Sarah imagined she would pay for her foolish decision to trust him. That some Tribesman would shoot an arrow or cut her throat."

    old "An ambush of some kind."
    new "An ambush of some kind."

    old "But nothing happened."
    new "But nothing happened."

    old "Instead, they simply rode through the open gate, into the city of Calshure."
    new "Instead, they simply rode through the open gate, into the city of Calshure."

    old "Behind her, she heard the creaking of the heavy gates as they fell shut with a loud slam."
    new "Behind her, she heard the creaking of the heavy gates as they fell shut with a loud slam."

    old "Now she was truly alone."
    new "Now she was truly alone."

    old "As she rode through the city street, Sarah saw the surprised looks on the faces of just about everyone."
    new "As she rode through the city street, Sarah saw the surprised looks on the faces of just about everyone."

    old "Her own people, stunned to see their leader return. To be here, without an army."
    new "Her own people, stunned to see their leader return. To be here, without an army."

    old "The Tribesman, who looked on with equal surprise that their enemy had just decided to ride into the city without guards."
    new "The Tribesman, who looked on with equal surprise that their enemy had just decided to ride into the city without guards."

    old "Just about everyone thought she had gone mad."
